Sample Problem

Fit an ARIMA(p,d,q) model to Lake Data. 

# loading package 
library(datasets)
library(DT)
data(LakeHuron)
# Plotting
plot(LakeHuron,type="o",xlab="Annual")

The plot of series does not show seasonality but it may suggest a trend. I can see a positive dependence also.

1. Examine ACF and PACF 

library(itsmr)
plota(LakeHuron)

The ACF shows a significant decaying up to lag 10 and the two first PACF coefficients are significant. The data suggests an AR(2) model.

2. Test Stationary hypothesis 

library(aTSA)
## 
## Attaching package: 'aTSA'
## The following object is masked from 'package:itsmr':
## 
##     forecast
## The following object is masked from 'package:graphics':
## 
##     identify
adf.test(LakeHuron)
## Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test 
## alternative: stationary 
##  
## Type 1: no drift no trend 
##      lag     ADF p.value
## [1,]   0 -0.0634   0.625
## [2,]   1 -0.2630   0.568
## [3,]   2 -0.1293   0.606
## [4,]   3 -0.1871   0.589
## Type 2: with drift no trend 
##      lag   ADF p.value
## [1,]   0 -2.94  0.0467
## [2,]   1 -3.90  0.0100
## [3,]   2 -3.09  0.0330
## [4,]   3 -2.85  0.0579
## Type 3: with drift and trend 
##      lag   ADF p.value
## [1,]   0 -3.14  0.1055
## [2,]   1 -4.15  0.0100
## [3,]   2 -3.38  0.0629
## [4,]   3 -2.99  0.1641
## ---- 
## Note: in fact, p.value = 0.01 means p.value <= 0.01

The test shows that the data is not stationary. This is expected because the data showed a trend component. Thus, we shall estimate and eliminate the trend.

3. Estimate the trend 

M=c("trend",1)
R=Resid(LakeHuron,M)
# Test stationary
adf.test(R)
## Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test 
## alternative: stationary 
##  
## Type 1: no drift no trend 
##      lag   ADF p.value
## [1,]   0 -3.19    0.01
## [2,]   1 -4.23    0.01
## [3,]   2 -3.45    0.01
## [4,]   3 -3.09    0.01
## Type 2: with drift no trend 
##      lag   ADF p.value
## [1,]   0 -3.17  0.0254
## [2,]   1 -4.21  0.0100
## [3,]   2 -3.42  0.0137
## [4,]   3 -3.07  0.0349
## Type 3: with drift and trend 
##      lag   ADF p.value
## [1,]   0 -3.14  0.1055
## [2,]   1 -4.15  0.0100
## [3,]   2 -3.38  0.0629
## [4,]   3 -2.99  0.1641
## ---- 
## Note: in fact, p.value = 0.01 means p.value <= 0.01
# Test iid hypothesis
test(R)
## Null hypothesis: Residuals are iid noise.
## Test                        Distribution Statistic   p-value
## Ljung-Box Q                Q ~ chisq(20)    107.83         0 *
## McLeod-Li Q                Q ~ chisq(20)     68.71         0 *
## Turning points T     (T-64)/4.1 ~ N(0,1)        40         0 *
## Diff signs S       (S-48.5)/2.9 ~ N(0,1)        50    0.6015
## Rank P         (P-2376.5)/162.9 ~ N(0,1)      2344    0.8419

The ADF test suggests that the data is stationary where the model is with no trend and no drift. However, the IID test rejected the null hypothesis of IID noise, therefore we need to fit an ARMA(p,q) to the residuals R.

4.Fit AR(2) 

# Fit model 1
ar.model= arima(R,order = c(2,0,0))
ar.model
## 
## Call:
## arima(x = R, order = c(2, 0, 0))
## 
## Coefficients:
##          ar1      ar2  intercept
##       1.0047  -0.2919     0.0196
## s.e.  0.0977   0.1004     0.2351
## 
## sigma^2 estimated as 0.4571:  log likelihood = -101.25,  aic = 210.5
# CI
confint(ar.model)
##                2.5 %      97.5 %
## ar1        0.8133033  1.19613040
## ar2       -0.4887323 -0.09514431
## intercept -0.4410414  0.48034102
The model has a significant AR coefficients but an intercept that is not significantly different than zero.
# Diagnostics model
test(ar.model$residuals)
## Null hypothesis: Residuals are iid noise.
## Test                        Distribution Statistic   p-value
## Ljung-Box Q                Q ~ chisq(20)      8.47    0.9883
## McLeod-Li Q                Q ~ chisq(20)      24.1    0.2379
## Turning points T     (T-64)/4.1 ~ N(0,1)        67    0.4682
## Diff signs S       (S-48.5)/2.9 ~ N(0,1)        50    0.6015
## Rank P         (P-2376.5)/162.9 ~ N(0,1)      2376    0.9976

Residuals are IDD.

5.Final equation of the model \[\begin{equation} X_t = m_t + Y_t \end{equation}\] where \[\begin{equation} m_t=580.2 - 0.02t \end{equation}\]

and \[\begin{equation} Y_t= Y_{t-1} - 0.292Y_{t-2} + Z_t \end{equation}\]

where \(Z_t \sim WN(0,0.457)\)

5. Comparing models 

# Fit model 1
model2= arima(R,order = c(2,0,0))
